{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601718/1938030601/0278.xml":{"full_text":"AMONG THE STAMP COLLECTORS\nNews of the Philatelic World, Its Interests and People\u2014Review of\nthe Stamp Press\u2014List of Local Meetings.\nBy James Waldo Fawcett.\nAn announcement is expected mo\nmentarily concerning the 1938 stamp\nprogram of the Post Office Depart\nment.\nThe fourth annual exhibition of the\nWashington Collectors' Club. National\nMuseum, Constitution avenue, opened\nThursday evening with a reception\n\u2666rendered by C. Hercus Just, presi\ndent, .to Government officials includ\ntng Third Assistant Postmaster Gen\neral Ramsey S. Black. Supt. of the\nDivision of Stamps Robert E. Fellers\n\u00abnd Philatelic Agent Otho Larkin\nRogers.\nPerhaps the most striking, beautiful\nentry is a drawing for a stamp in\ntribute to Gen. John J. Pershing, the\nwork of Edward B. Martin.\nOthers participating are: C. H.\nVaughan, who shows a complete sheet\nef 200 penny red 1858 stamps of Great\nBritain, reconstructed, as well as\nfisany fine ornamental envelopes of\nthe 19t,h century and a comprehensive\nIrsplay of British officials; F. A.\nWtckert, early German states and\nGerman Empire; Svend Yort, Neth\nerlands charities, Danzig complete\nexcept for three stamps and United\nStates commemoratives; C. Griscom\nRandle, jr\u201e Amundsen Polar Flight\ncover: D. H. and S. Reichgut, foreign\nfirst-day covers; Harry A. Fox. incased\nstamps used as coins, Afghanistan,\nAbyssinia and rare inverts of various\ncountries; E. L. Browne, miniature\nsheets and British colonies; Charles\nE. Trott, Minnesota Territory cancel\nlations, foreign and domestic postal\ncards and airmail covers; Frederick\nR. Rice, France and colonies, stamps\nrelating to music and musicians and\nUnited States first-day covers; Mrs.\nRice, Germany, and Luxembourg\nsemi-postals; H. E. Christ, Orange\nRiver Colony errors; Joseph G.\nDunn, coronation commemoratives\nand United States territorials; John\nC. Worthington, Russia and the\nFranco regime in Spain; Emile Zim\nmerman, postallyused British jubilees;\nJ. S. Petrie, Egypt; Benjamin C. Wal\ndenmaier, Sarawak; Miss Irene M.\nPistorio, Italian states and Italian\nreligious stamps; Miss Alice B. Cilley,\nsecretary of the Washington Airmail\nSociety, foreign airpost stamps: F. L.\nHiggins, Barbadoes, Canada, the Phil\nippiines and Ionian Islands: Miss Lulu\nWilliamson. 20th century Siam: Mrs.\nH. C. Workman, Switzerland, and\njubilee and coronation stamps of the\nBritish dominions; Russell Borhek,\n19 th century United States; Mrs.\nGrace L. MacKnight. philatelic cal\nendar of historic events and stamps\ndepicting childhood and womanhood:\nRobert A. Truax, \u201cfive\" and \u201cten\u201d\netampless covers; Constant Lambrette,\nMemel; Mrs. Clara B. Stowell. United\nStates Constitution commemoratives;\nMiss Viola Wildermuth, Army and\nNavy stamps and covers; T. Russell\nHungerford, foreign airpost covers;\nH. Gabriel, Scadta airmails.\nAlso, Miss Helen E. Voorhees, air\nmail covers; Ralph E. Smith, rare pre\ncancels; Mrs. Edna R. Trott, airmails,\nfirst voyages and first days; Francis\nB. Leech, experimental and pioneer\nflight covers; Mrs. J. R. D. Matheson,\nmilitary covers; Joseph A. Herbert,\nUnited States revenues; Mrs. Martin,\nairpost covers and hand-painted cov\ners from Japan; Mrs. Lila P. Wal\nlace, airmail topical subjects; and\nValdemar Weiergang, philaetlic liter\nature and medals, Norway No. 1\nplated, Goya Desnuda sheet of Spain\nand Wagner sheets of Germany.\nMr. Just\u2019s personal showing in\ncludes United States 19th century\ncovers, Canada and the Netherlands.\nThe Post Office Depart\"\u2019\u2014* con\ntributes two beautiful stamp mosaics\nof recent issues.\nAll material exhibited will remain\non display until March 31.\nClare Aubrey Huston, formerly chief\ndesigner of the Bureau of Engraving\nand Printing, died early Thursday\nmorning after two months' illness. He\nwas a native of Philadelphia, born De\ncember 1, 1858, and was appointed to\nhis first position in the bureau on\nNovember 24, 1902. During the next\n31 years he designed many of the most\nInteresting stamps and banknotes\nIssued by the Government.\nWhen informed of his death, H. M.\nSouthgate, president of the Bureau\nIssues Association, said: \u201cMr. Hus\nton. a kindly and agreeable man, was\na member of the old school. He did\nsome wonderful work for the bureau.\nHis drawing always was clearcut and\ndistinctive. Especially devoted to\nornamental detail, he laid down the\nprinciples of design which still are\nfollowed by the bureau artists. I am\n\u2022orry that he is gone.\u201d\nAlvin W. Hall, director of the bu\nreau, also paid tribute to Mr. Huston.\n\u201cHe had no superior,\u201d he declared.\n\u201cIndeed, his work was altogether\nunique. There was no other individual\nSTAMPS.\nUYENO\u2019S STAMP SHOP\n1205 Penn. Ave. N.W.__Met. 9014\n200 CN80RTED BRITISH COLONIALS.\n25c; 260 Newfoundland and Canada. 25c.\nRare bargains. Marigold Stamps. Toronto.\nCanada.__\nSTAMPS FOR COLLECTORS\nPOTOMAC STAMP SHOP. 913 G ST. N.W.\nSTAMPS\u2014COINS\u2014AUTOGRAPHS\nBought and Sold\nHOBBY SHOP\nTIB 17th St. N.W._District 1272\nNATIONAL STAMP MART\n1817 F St N.W., Bin. 411, Di\u00bbt, 8217\nChristopher Columbus Airmail! This\nbeautiful Spanish Issue, a comulete Hun\ngarian set; King Edward set; Mussolini on\nHorseback; Italian Foundation of Rome\nset; this entire group of set (with Ap\nprovals! for only 10c! PEARSON BROS.,\n88 Nassau St.. Dep\u2019t. 7B. New York.\nWHITNEY\u2019S STAMP M ART\n402 12th St. N.W. Met. 1511.\n\u201cCONSTITUTIONS\u201d\nFrom Brasil. 5g: France. 12e; Honduras.\n45e; Guatemala'/Sheet), \u00ab5c; Ecuador (14/.\n1.10; Niearauguab(12>, 83.25. Many bar\ngains In U. S. and Foreign.\nHARRY B. MASON. 918 F N.W._\nFIDELITY STAMP CO.\n945 Pa. Ave., Room 27 District 5130\nPANAMA OLYMPIC MINIATURE SHEET\npictured in ten colors, Including gold, and\nKrtraylnr 5 dffferei.t sport subieeu:\nxers In action (flrst time Illustrated on\nany stamp), etc., also coat of arms. Only\n30.000 sheets have been Issued, and Im\nmediately Mid eat. Prices arc skyrocket\ning now and dealers all ever the world\nweald gladly pay more than oar sensation\nally low price of 50c\u2014offered to approval\napplicants only. Write at once! HARRI\nSON STAMP CO., Pept. K-l. Harrison,\nT MAIL AUCTION\nA chance to purchase STAMPS at your\nOWN price 800 lots to be sold to\nthe highest bidders. To be held on March\n18th lots may nt examined at our\n\u2022tore dally from 9 am. to ti p.m.\nCatalogue free on request.\nWashington Stamo Co.. 937 Pa. Ave. N.W.\nlike him in the Government service.\nAn exceedingly able designer, he was\nabove all a gentleman of noble char\nacter.\u201d\nA check list of the stamps designed\nby Mr. Huston was prepared by Mrs.\nCatherine L. Manning, philatelic cu\nrator of the Smithsonian Institution.\nIt includes 2-cent Washington shield,\n1903; Louisiana Purchase series, 1904;\n1- cent Franklin, 1908; Lincoln cen\ntenary, 1909; Alaska-Yukon, 1909;\nPanama-Pacific series, 19)2; parcel\npost series, 1912-1913; 24-cent airmail,\n1918; 3-cent Victory, 1919; Pilgrim\nseries, 1920; 5-cent Theodore Roose\nvelt, 1922; 25-cent Niagara Falls, 1922;\n50-cent Arlington Amphitheater. 1922;\n3-cent Lincoln, 1923; 15-cent Statue\nof Liberty, 1923; 30-cent bison, 1923;\n$1 Lincoln Memorial, 1923; $2 Capj\ntol, 1923; $5 Genius of Freedom, 1923;\n8-cent airmail, 1923; 16-cent airmail,\n1923; 'i-cent. Nathan Hale, 1925;\n2- cent Norse American, 1925; 17-cent\nWoodrow Wilson, 1925; 2-cent Liberty\nBell, 1926; 2-cent White Plains, 1926;\n5-cent Ericsson, 1926; 10-cent map\nairmail, 1926; 5-cent Aeronautics Con\nference, 1928; 2-cent, George Rogers\nClark, 1929: 2-cent Sullivan Expedi\ntion, 1929; 2-cent Yorktown, 1931;\nState# Postage Currency\u201d; second\nsecond prize. Mannel Hahn, Win\nnetka, HI., \"General Issue of 1869\u201d;\nthird prize, Ralph W. Anderson,\nDorchester, Mass., \"Guam and Its\nStamps\"; honorable mention, William\nJ. Curran, Washington, \"Stampless\nCovers in the National Archives\u201d;\nT. Russell Hungerford, Washington,.\n\"United States No. 594,\u201d and Charles\nPazar, New York City, \u201cNational\nParks Series of 1934.\u201d\nMr. Hahn also was commended for\na monograph on the Trans-Mississippi\nseries of 1898.\nLiechtenstein announces two beau\ntiful additions to the current pictorial\nseries. One stamp\u201460rp, maroon and\nbuff\u2014shows Baron von Brandis of\nVaduz with his castle behind him;\nthe other\u201490rp, dark gray and buff\u2014\nrepresents the Drei Schwestern Moun\ntains.\nBritish Guiana has a new map\nstamp\u20144c, black and red, showing an\noutline of South America, with the\ncolony indicated in solid color.\nSwitzerland announces a new series\nof postage dues with large white\nnumerals on a plain carmine back\nThomas Robert Henry, jr., 11 years old, is starting a stamp\ncareer whose possibilities are infinite. He is the son of the\nscience editor of The Star and has, hie lather\u2019s help in the\ndevelopment of his collection. Also, 'ne finds ^fftaY 'fhaWy other\nboys at the Janney School and in the immediate neighborhood\nof his home, 3816 Albemarle street N.W., are devoted to the\nphilatelic hobby, interested in trading specimens.\n\u2014Photo by Harry Goodman, Star Staff.\n2-cent, 6-cent, 8-cent and 9-cent\nWashington Bicentennial, 1932; 3-cent\nDaniel Webster, 1632, and 3-cent\nOglethorpe, 1933.\nDavid H. Davenport, writing in Me\nkeel\u2019s Weekly Stamp News for Feb\nruary 21. says: \"Speculators must\nhave suffered a shock when it be\ncame known this last week that the\nPost Office Department had ordered\nprinted another million of the 15\ncent sepia airmail stamp of 1926.\nThe bureau\u2019s reserve had become ex\nhausted, and many collectors antici\npated the removal of this item from\nthe Philatelic Agency\u2019s sales list. The\nstamp, however, meets the require\nments of the airmail rate to. certain\nSouth American countries.\u201d\nAs previously announced in the news\ncolumns of The Star, Pan-American\nAirways has been awarded the con\ntract for airpost service between the\nUnited States and Bermuda. The\nfirst flight is scheduled to leave Balti\nmore on Wednesday, March 16. Ar\nrangements have been made for a\nspecial cachet and for appropriate\nmarkings at the terminal in Hamil\nton. The rate will be 10 cents per\nhalf ounce. Collectors may address\ncovers to themselves or other persons,\naffixing United States stamps and\nforwarding the ready-to-go letters to\nthe postmaster at Baltimore. Such\nmail will be returned by ordinary\nmeans to the addressees.\nMiss Mollie Lewis, an active member\nof the Washington Federation of Jun\nior Stamp Collectors, played a leading\nrole in last Monday evening\u2019s dramati\nzation of the castle stamps of Luxem\nbourg, presented by the Washington\nStamp Club of the Air over Station\nWOL.\nSt. Louis collectors have invited the\nFourth American Philatelic Congress\nto meet in their city.\nRalph E. Carpenter, once well\nknown among junior collectors in\nWashington, has returned to the city,\ngrown up and with four years of\nuniversity and seafaring experience to\nquicken his enthusiasm for stamps.\nThe Royal Philatelic Society of Lon\ndon has announced the names of\nmembers to serve on a committee to\narrange for the celebration of the\ncentenary of the postage stamp. Sir\nJohn Wilson is chairman, and he will\nhave associated with him the fol\nlowing collectors: John Hall Barron,\nR. F. A. Riesco, Eric W. Mann and\nL. C. C. Nicholson. It is understood\nthat P. L. Pemberton and Frank God\nden, representing the dealers\u2019 frater\nnity, will co-operate.\nR. L. Cullum, president of the Phil\natelic Society of the Oranges, N. J\u201e\nhas joined the Washington Philatelic\nSociety. He is well known as the\nsponsor of the courses In philately now\nbeing given at the South Orange\nMaplewood Adult Evening School un\nder the management of Winthrop 8.\nBoggs.\nMax G. Johl, writing in Stamps\nMagazine for March 5, says of the\nillustrations law: \u201cWe believe that the\nPost Office Department has done\neverything within its power to ac-*\ncommodate the wishes of collectors and\nis deserving of a vote of thanks.\u201d\nPhilip H. Ward, jr., formerly of\nWashington, now a resident of Phila\ndelphia, is the author of a special\nstudy of the early stamps of Brazil\nnow running in Mekeel's Weekly\nStamp News.\nDoris C. Kiley wTites: \u201cHave you\nnoticed the color variations of the\n3-cent Virgin Islands stamp? The\ncolors range from a light violet to a\nvery deep purple.\u201d\nWinners in Mekeel\u2019s Weekly manu\nscript contest are announced as fol\nlows: First prize, Albert W. Hitch\ncock, Chicago, United\nground. Values are 5, 10, 15, 20, 25,\n30, 40 and 50 cents.\nProm Egypt three Radio Congress\nstamps have been received. The de\nsign includes the Pyramids of Ghizeh\nand the Colossos of Thebes with a\nwireless tower and aerial. Denomi\nnations are: 5m, red brown: 15m,\ndark violet, and 20m, deep blue.\nStamp meetings for the week are\nlisted as follows: Tomorrow evening\nat 7:30, Washington Stamp Club of\nthe Air, from Station WOL. Albert\nF. Kunze will tell the story of Gabriele\nd'Annunzio and the stamps of Fiume\nand will comment on current phila\ntelic events.\nTuesday evening at 8, Washington\nCollectors\u2019 Club, Branch 5. Society of\nPhilatelic Americans, Thomson School,\nTwelfth street. Program, exhibition,\nbourse and auction.\nWednesday evening at 8, Washing\nton Philatelic Society, Hotel Carlton,\nSixteenth street. Business program\nfor members only.\nSaturday afternoon at 1, Philatelic\nLuncheon Group, Hotel Harrington,\nEleventh street. Round table discus\nsion of stamp news.\nSaturday afternoon at 5:30, Na\ntional Federation of Stamp Clubs\u2019\nbroadcast, red network, N. B. C., Sta\ntion WRC.\nIn Local Bridge Circles\nBlackwood Convention Finds Favor Here.\nBy Frank B. Lord.\nBRIDGE pointer: when leader\nwins the first trick in suit\ndeclaration and dummy shows\na void suit or a singleton it is\ngenerally advisable for the leader to\nlay down a trump in an effort to ex\nhaust dummy of trumps as soon as\npossible and prevent declarer from\nruffing losing tricks from his ov/n\nhand.\nWASHINGTON contract player*\narp being introduced to a new\nbidding convention which has been\nsuccessfully used in some of the Mid\nwest bridge centers. It is known as\nthe Blackwood convention and origi\nnated in Indianapolis, where it has\nbecome very popular among the ex\nperts. It is a modification of the\nFour-Five no-trump convention and\nwhen properly applied is said to pro\nduce accurate results and to enable\na player to reach a slam contract\nwhich would not be possible under the\nFour-Five method, without assuming\na risk that might prove disastrous.\nIn its artificiality it is similar to that\nconventon, but is far better in en\nabling the bidder to locate aces and\nkings if in partner\u2019s hand.\nThe Blackwood Convention provides\nthat where a player makes an orig\ninal bid of one and his partner gives\nhim a jump in that suit, if the orig\ninal bid warrants it the bidder may\ngive a four no-trump call in an ef\nfort to determine aces held by part\nner. Partner's response is artificial.\nIf he has no aces he bids five clubs;\nwith one ace, five diamonds; with two\naces, five hearts; with three aces,\nfive spades; with all four aces, five\nno-trump. After such response, if\nless than five no-trump, the original\nbidder himself bids five no-trump,\nseeking to find kings. Partner makes\nsimilar response except that it is\nbased upon the number of kings held.\nThus, partner bids six clubs holding\nno kings, six diamonds holding one\nking and so on. The user, however,\nmust be prepared to play at the six\nlevel, if partner responds in a suit\nhigher than the suit originally bid.\nHere is an example: North holds:\nSpades, A. 7; hearts, A, 7, 4; dia\nmonds, Q. 9. 6, 2; clubs, K, 5, 3, 2.\nNorth opens with a bid of one dia\nmond and without intervening bid\nSouth jumps to three diamonds. Un\nder the Four-Five convention North\nwould bid four no-trump, holding two\naces and the king of his bid suit and\nSouth showing a fit. South would\nthen respond with five no-trump, in\ndicating the other two aces. North\nwould then bid six diamonds. If\nNorth were assured, however, that his\npartner also held an outside king\nupon which he could discard his small\nclub, seven would be a lay-down.\nOtherwise bidding seven would be a\ngamble.\nUnder the Blackwood convention\nNorth would bid fouf no trump for a\nslam try after his partner had jumped\nhis original bid to three diamonds.\nNorth is prepared to play six diamonds\nif South has two aces and responds\nwith five diamonds, which forces him\nto the six level. South, in responding\nto the four no trump bid, shows his\ntwo aces by bidding five hearts. North\nthen goes to five no trump, seeking\ninformation about partner\u2019s kings. If\nSouth has no kings he will sign off\nwith six club6, and North is still able\nto bid six diamonds, but South has the\nclub king, so he bids himself six dia\nmonds. North then knows that a\ngrand slam can be made, and accord\ningly bids seven diamonds.\nPlayers point out that the one dan\nger in the Blackwood convention 1s\nthat some users are not prepared to\nplay a higher contract after the part\nner has given a positive response that\nforces the auction to a higher level in\nthe trump suit originally named.\nThe Blackwood 'Convention is not\npublished in any volume as a part of\nanybody\u2019s system of bidding, but\nWashington bridge fans have met up\nwith it when playing with opponents\nfrom other cities, notably those from\nMidwest cities. Some of the local ex\nperts are disposed to give it a try\nout, realizing, however, that there\nmust be a perfect understanding of\nthe convention between the players.\nHands which afford an opportunity for\nits use, as well as for the Four-Five no\ntrump convention are .somewhat rare.\noccurring generally not more than two\nor three times in a session, yet average\nplayers use the latter more or less\nsuccessfully when there is occasion\nfor it.\nUJ M. MCINTYRE and Le Roy\nThurtell, winners in the special\nduplicate held under the auspices of\nthe Washington Bridge League, which\nqualified them to represent Washing\nton in the Southeastern championship\ngames at Hollywood, Fla., to be held\nMarch 10 to 13, inclusive, left here by\nautomobile yesterday for the Florida\nresort, to participate in the bridge\nevents. They expect to make arrange\nments for partners in the mixed-pair\ngame on Thursday night. On Friday\nafternoon will occur the women\u2019s pair\ngame and on Friday night and Satur\nday afternoon the two preliminary\nsessions of the open-pair contest in\nwhich they hope to qualify for the\nfinals on Saturday night. Besides the\nprizes, master points will be awarded,\n15 to the winners, 9 to the runner-up\npair and 3 to the third pair.\nThe team of four match will be\nplayed on Sunday afternoon and eve\nning. All teams will play in both\nsessions. Mr. McIntyre and Mr. Thur\ntell expect to team up with John C.\nKunkel, jr., of Harrisburg. Pa., and\na partner whom he will select. Mr.\nKunkel is now spending several weeks\nat St. Petersburg, Fla. Master points\nin this event will be 9 to the winners\nand 5 to members of the runner-up\nteam. As special awards to those suc\ncessful in this match there will be\nentrance fees and perhaps a part of\nexpenses to the annual summer tour\nnament of the American Contract\nBridge League at Asbury Park.\nAfter the Hollywood tournament Mr.\nMcIntyre, who formerly lived at Clear\nwater, Fla., will spend two weeks visit\ning his old home, and perhaps teach\ning some of the natives a few of the\nthings he has learned about contract\nduring his residence and successful\nbridge playing in Washington.\n^LTHOUGH suffering the biggest\nslump they have had, the Ranger\nteam playing in the second half of the\nseason tournament of the Federal\nBridge at Wardman Park Hotel on\nTuesday night, still retained leader\nship with a total of 94\u2019- boards. They\nwon only eight boards at this session\nagainst 11 \\2 won by the Lions and\n10'2 won by the Arlington team. The\nlatter team, winners in the first half\nof the tournament, after dropping\nbadly behind have now recovered from\ntheir slump and are in second place\nwith 891 t boards. The Lions, who fell\nto sixth place a week ago, recovered\nsomewhat by winning 111 a boards, a\ntop for the section, and are now in\nthird place. Secag. in second place a\nweek ago. by winning only 7 boards\nfell to 87*2, a three-way tie for fourth\nplace with the Just Us team and the\nPost Office team. Just Us won 10\nboards and Post Office eight, making\nthe total of each of these three 87 *3\nboards.\nIn section B the Coast Survey team\nwon 11'2 boards for a top in that sec\ntion. The Ladies P. W. A. team, play\ning in section C, introduced a male\nsubstitute last Tuesday evening, Maj.\nSchutte, and succeeded not only in\nmaking top in their section but their\nscore of 1312 boards was the highest\nin any section. Mrs. Schware, Mrs.\nGleim and Miss Connerton were the\nother members of the team.\nThree more games remain to be\nplayed before the close of the tourna\nment.\nIN THE Fairfax Hotel game on Tues\nday afternoon the winners were:\nNorth and south, Mrs. Charles Kav\nanaugh and Mrs. N. T. N. Robinson,\nfirst: Mrs. C. W. Zimmer and Mrs.\nHarold Young, second; Mrs. Oliver\nHoyem and Mrs. Robert Du Bois,\nthird; east and west, Mrs. W. L.\nClark and Mrs. G. G. Bradley, first;\nMrs. W. T. Tisdell and Mrs. E. P.\nWalton, second; Mrs. Lester D.\nJohnson and H. Au, third.\nWednesday morning\u2014Mrs. Oliver\nHoyem and Mrs. T. D. Sheldon, first:\nMrs. Menne Barry and Mrs. J. R.\nBelt, second: Mrs. N. T. N. Robinson\nand Mrs. Charles Kavanaugh, third.\nFriday evening\u2014Dr. A. J. Steinberg\nand J. D. Granger, first; Miss H. G.\nByers and G. H. Warthen, second;\nNEWS OF THE MOTORING WORLD\nNational Used-Gar Exchange Week Expected to Aid Auto Industry\nand Put Recovery Wheels in Motion.\nBy G. Adams Howard.\nTHE National Capital la partici\npating, along with its sister\nStates, In what is known as\nnational used car Exchange\nweek. This plan of some 46,000 auto\nmobile dealers throughout the Nation\nwill continue through next Saturday.\nIts purpose is to stimulate the auto\nmotive business by looking after that\nperennial trouble, the used car mar\nket. Once the old cars get moving\nagain from parking and storage lots,\nthe newer machines will start also.\nThe plan was to a great extent the\nresult of the recent conference in\nWashington of leading manufacturers\nand President Roosevelt. It was felt\nthat if the automobile industry, one\nso important in the United States,\nbecause of its dependent lines, once\ngot under way, that other businesses\nwould pick up, too.\nThe one-week campaign, designed\nto stimulate used car sales and start\nthe wheels of recovery in motion,\nstarted yesterday. It is sponsored by\nthe entire automobile industry, which\nunited action is a new step in auto\nmotive history.\n\u201cNo better contribution to business\nrevival could be made,\" E. M. Lied,\npresident of the National Automobile\nDealers\u2019 Association, stated.\nIn urging all automobile dealers to\ngive their wholehearted support to this\nunited industry movement, he said he\nwas convinced that it offers them a\ngolden opportunity to reduce their\npresent used car dollar inventory by\ntrading down late model, high-priced\nmerchandise, thereby improving their\nfinancial position and providing ad\nditional working capital.\nNational Used Car Exchange Week\nalso provides the industry the oppor\ntunity of once again assuming leader\nship in a Nation-wide campaign to\nstimulate business in all lines, he con- i\ntinued. No greater contribution to\nward business revival could be made\nthan one which points the way to re\nemployment of the millions of our\ncountrymen who are now idle.\nThe important part played by the\nautomotive industry in the Nation's\neconomic scheme is not generally rec\nognized. Statistics show that one out\nof seven gainfully employed in this\ncountry depend, for a living, upon\nthe automobile industry or the thou\nsands of business enterprises directly\nand indirectly connected with it.1\nAgnes McNutt and Kathleen McNutt. I\nthird.\nAt the La Sallp Bridge Studio, Mon\nday evening\u2014Miss Lylia Cook and\nMrs. Grace Thames, first: Mr. and\nMrs. Leo V. Crane, second: F. J. Par\nsons and E. L. Scott, third.\nTuesday afternoon\u2014Mrs. Jack Ben\nnett and John Donnolly, first; Mrs.\nCharles Kavanaugh and Mrs. N. T.\nN. Robinson, second; Gen. E. F. Mc\nGlachlin and Lt. Col. E. B. Gray,\nthird.\nAt the University Club\u2014Vladimir\nSveshnikoff and C. B. Pennebaker,\nfirst; Mrs. John Mothershed and\nGeorge S. Ward, second; George W.\nSpangler and W. W. Flack, third.\nAt the Shoreham. Monday after\nnoon\u2014Mrs. Peyton Blamire and Mrs.\nJack Bennett, first; Mrs. Menne Barry\nand Mrs. N. T. N. Robinson, second.\nAt the Shoreham, Tuesday eve\nning\u2014Mr. and Mrs. A. P. Stockvis,\nfirst; Mrs. M. R. West and Tom Ham\nlin, second; Mrs. C. W. Zimmer and\nJohn Donnelly, third.\n^WASHINGTON players are inter\nested in and some of them will\nparticipate in the following scheduled\ntournaments, where master points will\nbe awarded: Old Dominion, in Alex\nandria, Va., March 25-27; Anthracite\ntournament, Wilkes-Barre, April 1-3;\nSoutheastern Pennsylvania tourna\nment. York, Pa.. April 8-9; Skytop\ntournament. Skytop. Pa., May 6-8,\nand Canadian-American champion\nships, Niagara Falls, N. Y., May 19-22.\nTN ONE of the rare instances when\na physic bid is highly profitable,\nMrs. J. W. Hussey won next to top in a\nrecent duplicate game on a deal in\nwhich she was set five tricks.\nEast and West were vulnerable;\nNorth and South not vulnerable.\nTherefore, any movement which serves\nto stimulate the Increased purchas\ning and use of motor vehicles imme\ndiately and directly affects, bene\nficially, the employment and earnings\nof a large mass of our population.\nConsequently, the campaign now be\ning undertaken by the entire auto\nmobile Industry to stimulate public in\nterest in automobile ownership and\nto urge the millions of car owners to\ntrade in their older model used cars,\nat this time, for later ones which offer\nmore modern, more economical, more\nefficient and safer transportation, is,\nin my opinion, highly commendable.\nNever before have there been avail\nable such genuine used car values at\nfair prices. It is safe to say that every\none who now owns an older model used\ncar would like to convert it into more\ndesirable low-cost transportation with\nin the limits of his or her pocket\nbook. This campaign seeks to crystal\nlize that desire into action.\nIt is generally recognized today, Mr.\nLied pointed out, that the, unused\ntransportation value remaining in\nused cars today is greatly ihcreased\nover what it was a few years ago.\nThe high degree of engineering skill,\nthe almost incredible improvements\nin design and in the life of the com\nponent parts of automobiles built dur\ning the past five years have resulted in\ndeveloping motor vehicles which of\nfer the used car buyer the utmost in\nvalue for his expenditure, he con\ntinued.\nThe importance of the used car\nmarket is something we should not\noverlook. Very definitely, automobile j\nretailing is now a replacement busi- j\nness. For the past decade our sales\npenetration has been vertical rather1\nthan lateral, through extending auto- j\nmobile ownership down into the lower\nincome groups. Latest figures indi\ncate that approximately nine million\npresent car owners comprise those\nearning less than $1,000 a year.\nSixty-six per cent of our sales are\ni constantly made to used car buyers\u2014\npeople who never buy a new automo\nbile. It is. therefore, highly desirable\nthat automobile dealers cultivate this\nmarket intensively and, above all, see\nthat the treatment of the huge mar\nj ket is such that it builds confidence\nj in us as automobile merchants and\nJ prestige for the used motor vehicles\nj to be sold.\nMr. Lied said that the success of\nNational Used Car Exchange Week de\nNorth was dealer on the following\nhand:\nNorth.\nS\u201410 x x x x x\nH\u2014Q\nD\u2014x x x\nC\u2014X X X\nWest. Blast.\nS\u2014J 8\u2014A K Q x x\nH\u2014A 9 x x x H\u2014x\nD\u2014A Q x x D\u2014x x x\nC\u2014A x x C\u2014K Q J x\nSouth.\nS\u2014x\nH\u2014K J 10 X X X\nD\u2014K J x\nC\u201410 x x\nJudge Hussey, sitting North and\ndealing, suspected from his own hand\nthat East and West held game going\nand possibly slam going cards and, not j\nbeing vulnerable, bid one spade. East,\nwith three top honors and two others\nin that suit, thought it best not to\ndouble, especially as he expected a bid\nof two hearts from either South or\nWest. East passed, and South bid two\nhearts: West feared to double that\nbid. believing that if he did so North\nwould bid two spades, and he accord\ningly passed, and Judge Hussey, to\nj make certain that his adversaries, both\nj of whom had passed, did not suspect\nhim and make a game bid. raised to\nthree hearts. Neither East or West\ndoubled, although the hand was set\nfive tricks. Notwithstanding that\nloss Mrs. Hussey\u2019s rating on the board\nwas second, because other players. East\nand West, had either made a game vul\nj nerable by bidding at least three no\ntrump and making five for a score of\n660, or. as one pair did. make six\nclub6. Instead of losing 1,370 points in\nthe case of the small slam club bid\nI der and 660 in the case of the five no\ni trump bidder, the Husseys lost only\nI 250 points on the board.\npends largely upon the manner In\nwhich Joint efforts of dealers stimu\nlate not only their own business, but\nall business.\nImmediately prior to the present\ngeneral business recession, cities and\ncounties depending extensively upon\nautomobile manufacture ranked among\nthe lowest in unemployment and\nrelief.\nThe Automobile Manufacturers As\nsociation today announced that a\ntabulation mad* from the United\nStates unemployment census figures,\ntaken November 16-20, ranking all\nautomobile centers and all counties\nwhich were over 250,000 population at\nthe last general census, shows that four\nof the five counties which had the\nlowest percentage of population unem\nployed or on W. P. A. or other made\nwork were automobile production cen\nters. All but two automotive centers\nranked below the national average.\nThe table, showing this ranking,\nwith automotive cities underscored, is\nattached.\nThese figures clarify the re-employ\nment performance of the automobile\nindustry up to the end of 1937. The\nsubsequent decline in employment all\nover the country may have affected\nthe standing of various localities in\nrelative burden of unemployment.\nHowever, the present impact found\nautomobile cities in the more favor\nable positions for meeting the problem.\nA recent edition of one of the news\nreels pictured the destruction of hun\ndreds of obsolete automobiles as the\nvery latest in highway safety cam\npaigns. These cars had been declared\nunsafe for further use. They were\ngathered together and liberally doused\nwith kerosene. Set afire, they went up\nin a gigantic blaze. Those present\nat this exhibition congratulated them\nselves on having rid the roads of\nthese defective motor vehicles which\nhad added to the dangers of driving.\n\"It is too bad,\u2019\u2019 declared Charles M.\nUpham, engineer-director of the\nAmerican Road Builders Association,\n\"that the obsolete, unsafe roads of\nAmerica cannot be gathered in one\nspot and destroyed. Getting rid of old\nand unsafe cars does away with only\na few of the hazards of driving. The\nmost modem automobiles, equipped\nwith all the latest safety features, will\ncontinue to be involved in serious\ntraffic accidents unless safety is also\nbuilt into our highways. Defective\ncars may be blamed for some of the\n40,000 traffic-accident deaths during\n1937, but at least 50 per cent of them\ncould have been avoided by the con\nstruction of up-to-date, safe roads.\nThe worn-out, antiquated road is the\nmost relentless of all death traps.\u201d\nFactory sales of automobiles manu\nfactured in the United States (in\ncluding foreign assemblies from pafts\nmade in the United States and re\nported as complete units or vehicles'\nfor January, 1938, consisted of 210,450\nvehicles, of which 156.387 were pas\nsenger cars, and 54,063 were commer\ncial cars, trucks, and road tractors, as\ncompared with 326,234 vehicles in De\ncember, 1937, 379,603 vehicles in Jan\nuary, 1937, and 363.942 vehicles in\nJanuary, 1936. These statistics, com\nprising data for the entire industry,\nwere released today by Director Wil\nliam L. Austin, Bureau of the Census,\nDepartment of Commerce.\nCheering sales reports will hold car\nand truck production firm at 57,879\nunits the week ending February 26.\nwith the likelihood operations gen\nerally will be speeded as preparations\nbegin for the indicated spring up\nswing, Automotive Daily News says\nin its mid-week sftrvey of the industry.\nA. D. N.'s projection compares with\na revised total of 58.073 units for thp\nweek ended February 19. and 108.909\nunits in the corresponding week of\n1937.\nIncluding the current week's esti\nmate, February's total to date now\nrests at 207.948 units. Combined with\naround 12,000 units, which figure to\nbe turned out next Monday, the Feb\nruary grand total should hover around\nthe 220.000 mark, which would com\npare with 383.698 jobs produced in\nFebruary, 1937.\nLikelihood of increased operations\non all fronts starting in March is in\ndicated in several quarters.\nTHOSE WERE THE 